MATCH_TOOL: Edit|Write
MATCH_PATTERN: apps/client/src/(store/useGameStore\.ts|shells/.*\.tsx?)$
ADVISORY: |
  (Skip if your edit doesn't add or modify a `select...` export / a
  `useGameStore(s => ...)` callsite that constructs a fresh object or array.)

  React 19 + Zustand gotcha that crashes the Pulse shell with "Maximum update
  depth exceeded" / "getSnapshot should be cached to avoid an infinite loop":

  A Zustand selector that BUILDS a new object or array literal on every call
  returns a fresh reference each render. Zustand compares with `Object.is`, so
  the snapshot looks "changed" → React re-renders → selector runs again →
  new reference → infinite loop.

  WRONG (fresh object/array every call):
    export const selectStandings = (state) =>
      Object.entries(state.roster).map(([id, p], i) => ({ id, player: p, rank: i + 1 }));

  `useShallow` DOES NOT fix this for arrays that contain fresh object literals —
  it compares array items by `Object.is`, so fresh inner objects still fail.

  RIGHT — wrap the selector with `memoSelector` (defined in useGameStore.ts).
  Declare the state slices the selector reads; the cache returns the same
  reference until one of those inputs changes identity:

    export const selectStandings = memoSelector(
      (s) => [s.roster],
      (state) => Object.entries(state.roster).map(([id, p], i) => ({ id, player: p, rank: i + 1 })),
    );

  Include EVERY state field the selector reads (directly or via nested
  selectors) in the inputs tuple — a missing input means stale data.

  For consumers: once the selector is memoized at the source, just use
  `useGameStore(selectX)` — no `useShallow` or `useMemo` needed at the call
  site. Do NOT return primitives from inside a fresh object (e.g.
  `useGameStore(s => selectX(s).length)` recomputes the whole selector each
  render; prefer a dedicated primitive selector or memoize the source).

  Rule: any selector exported from useGameStore.ts that returns a NEW object
  or array literal MUST be wrapped with `memoSelector`. Selectors that return
  a primitive (number/boolean/string) or an existing state reference do not
  need wrapping.
